        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nElizabeth is a 53-year-old female today complaining of chest pain and she has a past medical history of diabetes and high blood pressure.\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports chest pain every time she starts walking, describing it as a pressure and dull pain. She states this pain has been present for approximately three months and is exacerbated by walking. She reports that she has been trying to improve her diet and exercise regimen, but has struggled with sodas. Her blood sugars have been higher since she has not been able to be active. She has an ophthalmology appointment scheduled in two weeks. She reports no nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea related to her diabetes or medications. She also notes a history of high blood pressure documented by other clinicians, but not yet addressed with medication. The patient reports swelling in her lower legs.\nFindings\nThe examination reveals a two out of six systolic ejection murmur. The patient's lungs are clear, with no crackles or rhonchi. The heart rhythm is regular and rate is normal. Pulses are equal bilaterally. The abdomen is soft and non-tender. The back exam is unremarkable. Extremity exam reveals one plus edema in the ankles. There is no calf tenderness.\nAssessment",
